spec: decimal_extra1516
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(decimal)
docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html
provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html — decimal module Decimal class documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-12"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "IBM General Decimal Arithmetic specification"
  notes:
    - "Wave 548 (_extra1516): arithmetic/numeric operator __dict__ presence checks for decimal.Decimal."
    - "decimal.Decimal defines ALL standard arithmetic operators in its own __dict__: __add__, __radd__, __sub__, __rsub__, __mul__, __rmul__, __truediv__, __rtruediv__, __floordiv__, __rfloordiv__, __mod__, __rmod__, __pow__, __rpow__, __divmod__, __rdivmod__."
    - "This makes decimal.Decimal the richest class for the wave 548 arithmetic-operator theme — it defines every forward and reflected arithmetic operator."
    - "Decimal also defines unary arithmetic operators: __neg__, __pos__, __abs__."
    - "Contrast with: pathlib.PurePath (only __truediv__ + __rtruediv__), io classes (none), re classes (none)."
    - "All arithmetic operators are defined synchronously and implement IEEE 754 decimal arithmetic semantics."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-12."
  created_at: "2026-04-12T00:00:00Z"
error_model: python_exceptions

table decimal_extra1516.decimal_forward_arithmetic_ops:
  description: "decimal.Decimal forward arithmetic operator presence — __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__, __mod__, __pow__ are all defined in decimal.Decimal.__dict__; Decimal implements the full IEEE 754 arithmetic operator set; wave 548"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: arithmetic_ops
  id_prefix: dc1516fa
  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dc1516fa001,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__add__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__add__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __add__ in its own __dict__; Decimal + Decimal performs IEEE 754 decimal addition with exact precision; Decimal('1.1') + Decimal('2.2') == Decimal('3.3') (no floating-point rounding error); __add__ is defined on Decimal alongside all other arithmetic operators; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa002,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__sub__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__sub__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __sub__ in its own __dict__; Decimal - Decimal performs IEEE 754 decimal subtraction; Decimal('3.3') - Decimal('1.1') == Decimal('2.2'); __sub__ is one of the fourteen arithmetic operators (__add__, __radd__, __sub__, __rsub__, __mul__, __rmul__, __truediv__, __rtruediv__, __floordiv__, __rfloordiv__, __mod__, __rmod__, __pow__, __rpow__) all defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa003,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__mul__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__mul__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __mul__ in its own __dict__; Decimal * Decimal performs IEEE 754 decimal multiplication; Decimal('1.5') * Decimal('2') == Decimal('3.0'); multiplication preserves all significant digits with exact decimal arithmetic; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa004,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__truediv__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__truediv__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __truediv__ in its own __dict__; Decimal / Decimal performs IEEE 754 decimal true division; Decimal('1') / Decimal('3') == Decimal('0.3333333333333333333333333333') with default 28-digit precision; unlike pathlib.PurePath where __truediv__ means path joining, Decimal.__truediv__ means numeric division; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa005,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__floordiv__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__floordiv__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __floordiv__ in its own __dict__; Decimal // Decimal performs IEEE 754 integer-division (floor division); Decimal('7') // Decimal('2') == Decimal('3'); floor division returns an exact integer result as a Decimal; both __truediv__ (true division) and __floordiv__ (floor division) are defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa006,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__mod__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__mod__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __mod__ in its own __dict__; Decimal % Decimal computes the IEEE 754 decimal remainder; Decimal('7') % Decimal('2') == Decimal('1'); __mod__ and __floordiv__ are complementary: a == (a // b) * b + (a % b); both are defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa007,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__pow__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__pow__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __pow__ in its own __dict__; Decimal ** Decimal (or Decimal ** int) computes decimal exponentiation; Decimal('2') ** 10 == Decimal('1024'); Decimal('2') ** Decimal('0.5') computes the square root to context precision; __pow__ completes the set of seven forward arithmetic operators all defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516fa008,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__divmod__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__divmod__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __divmod__ in its own __dict__; divmod(Decimal('7'), Decimal('2')) returns (Decimal('3'), Decimal('1')) — the quotient and remainder as a tuple; __divmod__ combines __floordiv__ and __mod__ in a single IEEE 754 operation; verified with Python 3.14.3"]

table decimal_extra1516.decimal_reflected_arithmetic_ops:
  description: "decimal.Decimal reflected arithmetic operator presence — __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__, __rpow__ are all defined in decimal.Decimal.__dict__; Decimal supports reflected arithmetic to interoperate with int and other numeric types; wave 548"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: arithmetic_ops
  id_prefix: dc1516ra
  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dc1516ra001,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__radd__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__radd__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __radd__ in its own __dict__; __radd__ is invoked when the left operand does not support addition with a Decimal; 1 + Decimal('2') dispatches to Decimal.__radd__(1) if int.__add__ returns NotImplemented; __radd__ enables Decimal to participate in mixed-type arithmetic from the right side; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra002,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rsub__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rsub__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rsub__ in its own __dict__; __rsub__ handles the case where a Decimal is the right operand of subtraction and the left operand does not support subtraction with Decimal; __rsub__ is the reflected counterpart of __sub__; both are defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra003,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rmul__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rmul__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rmul__ in its own __dict__; __rmul__ handles multiplication where Decimal is the right operand; 2 * Decimal('3') may dispatch to Decimal.__rmul__(2); __rmul__ is the reflected counterpart of __mul__; both forward (__mul__) and reflected (__rmul__) multiplication are defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra004,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rtruediv__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rtruediv__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rtruediv__ in its own __dict__; __rtruediv__ handles division where Decimal is the divisor (right operand); 1 / Decimal('3') may dispatch to Decimal.__rtruediv__(1); both __truediv__ and __rtruediv__ are defined in Decimal.__dict__; contrast with pathlib.PurePath where __rtruediv__ means reversed path joining; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra005,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rfloordiv__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rfloordiv__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rfloordiv__ in its own __dict__; __rfloordiv__ handles floor division where Decimal is the right operand; both __floordiv__ and __rfloordiv__ are defined in Decimal.__dict__; the complete floor-division pair is present; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra006,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rmod__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rmod__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rmod__ in its own __dict__; __rmod__ handles modulo where Decimal is the right operand (divisor); both __mod__ and __rmod__ are defined in Decimal.__dict__; the complete modulo pair is present; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra007,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rpow__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rpow__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rpow__ in its own __dict__; __rpow__ handles exponentiation where Decimal is the exponent; 2 ** Decimal('10') may dispatch to Decimal.__rpow__(2); both __pow__ and __rpow__ are defined in Decimal.__dict__; the complete exponentiation pair is present; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra008,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rdivmod__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rdivmod__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __rdivmod__ in its own __dict__; __rdivmod__ is the reflected counterpart of __divmod__; it handles divmod() where Decimal is the right operand; both __divmod__ and __rdivmod__ are defined in Decimal.__dict__; Decimal implements the complete reflected arithmetic operator set; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ra009,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__rsub__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__rsub__') == True — summary confirmation: __rsub__ is defined in decimal.Decimal.__dict__; the complete set of fourteen forward + reflected arithmetic operators all present in Decimal.__dict__: __add__, __radd__, __sub__, __rsub__, __mul__, __rmul__, __truediv__, __rtruediv__, __floordiv__, __rfloordiv__, __mod__, __rmod__, __pow__, __rpow__; decimal.Decimal is uniquely comprehensive in the wave 548 survey; verified with Python 3.14.3"]

table decimal_extra1516.decimal_unary_arithmetic_ops:
  description: "decimal.Decimal unary arithmetic operator presence — __neg__, __pos__, __abs__ are all defined in decimal.Decimal.__dict__; also confirms __divmod__/__rdivmod__ present and cross-checks absent operators on non-numeric classes; wave 548"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: arithmetic_ops
  id_prefix: dc1516ua
  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dc1516ua001,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__neg__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__neg__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __neg__ in its own __dict__; -Decimal('1.5') == Decimal('-1.5'); unary negation applies the sign change to the Decimal value with full precision; __neg__ is one of three unary arithmetic operators (__neg__, __pos__, __abs__) all defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua002,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__pos__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__pos__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __pos__ in its own __dict__; +Decimal('-1.5') == Decimal('-1.5') (pos does not negate); unary positive applies the context rounding to the Decimal value; __pos__ is defined alongside __neg__ and __abs__ in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua003,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__abs__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__abs__') == True — decimal.Decimal defines __abs__ in its own __dict__; abs(Decimal('-1.5')) == Decimal('1.5'); absolute value returns a non-negative Decimal; __abs__ completes the three-operator unary arithmetic set defined in Decimal.__dict__; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua004,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__add__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__add__') == True — summary anchor: all seven forward arithmetic operators (__add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__, __mod__, __pow__) are defined in decimal.Decimal.__dict__; all seven reflected operators (__radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__, __rpow__) are defined; all three unary operators (__neg__, __pos__, __abs__) are defined; decimal.Decimal implements the complete IEEE 754 arithmetic operator protocol; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua005,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__mul__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__mul__') == True — summary anchor: decimal.Decimal.__dict__ contains all arithmetic operators including __mul__; in the wave 548 survey across four modules, decimal.Decimal is the only class that defines __mul__ and __rmul__; pathlib.PurePath defines __truediv__ only; io classes define no arithmetic operators; re classes define no arithmetic operators; Decimal is uniquely rich; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua006,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__floordiv__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__floordiv__') == True — summary anchor: decimal.Decimal defines __floordiv__ in its own __dict__; Decimal // Decimal computes floor division under IEEE 754; __floordiv__ and its reflected __rfloordiv__ are both defined; floor division on Decimal returns an exact integer-valued Decimal (e.g., Decimal('7') // Decimal('2') == Decimal('3') not Decimal('3.5')); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua007,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__mod__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__mod__') == True — summary anchor: decimal.Decimal defines __mod__ in its own __dict__; decimal modulo is computed as: a mod b = a - (a // b) * b using exact decimal arithmetic; __mod__ and __rmod__ are both present in Decimal.__dict__; modulo on Decimal preserves the sign of the divisor (IEEE 754 behavior); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua008,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__truediv__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__truediv__') == True — wave 548 cross-module comparison anchor: __truediv__ is defined in both decimal.Decimal.__dict__ (for numeric division) and pathlib.PurePath.__dict__ (for path joining); io classes (IOBase, BytesIO, StringIO) and re classes (Pattern, Match, error) do NOT define __truediv__ in their __dict__; Decimal.__truediv__ uses the current decimal Context for precision and rounding; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [dc1516ua009,
       decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__,
       ["__pow__"],
       true,
       "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__pow__') == True — summary: decimal.Decimal defines all seventeen arithmetic-related operators in its own __dict__: seven forward (__add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__, __mod__, __pow__), seven reflected (__radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__, __rpow__), two divmod forms (__divmod__, __rdivmod__), and three unary (__neg__, __pos__, __abs__); wave 548 confirms Decimal is the most arithmetically complete class across io, pathlib, re, and decimal; verified with Python 3.14.3"]
